name: NPR
text: A coalition of four ethnic parties forced out Ethiopia's dominant political party in 2018, putting in democratic reforms and a new president. But now that president has postponed elections and accused former allies of trying to tear the country apart. https://t.co/8FyrO5uAZQ

name: NPR
text: Fickle weather and fluctuating prices make farming risky, so five years ago, Paul Knowlton tried a new cash crop: solar energy. Now he's trying something brand new: Panels that collect energy, while still letting enough light through to grow crops. @WBUR https://t.co/oQ30LBDGYJ

name: NPR
text: For more than 35 years, a vacuum repairman in Massachusetts has invited strangers to a big, free Thanksgiving dinner. He can't do that this year, but he's got a different plan for sharing love and togetherness. @StoryCorps https://t.co/og08J3COUP

name: NPR
text: The title track on Chris Stapleton's new album, "Starting Over," seems ready-made for 2020, but the song came to him much earlier: "Sometimes, you write 'em and pull it back out and you listen to it, and maybe it means something else in a different time." https://t.co/Tq657XTEqU

name: NPR
text:
The DHS agency that oversees election security primarily intended to fight foreign disinformation about the election. 

It ended up rebutting rumors and baseless allegations spread by Trump.

Now, the agency's head expects to be fired by the White House.
https://t.co/1A8Ab6Y2as

name: NPR
text:
In a statement, cybersecurity officials called the 2020 election "the most secure in American history," saying, "there is no evidence that any voting system ... was in any way compromised."

One official says that was a direct response to a tweet by Trump. https://t.co/Wucbt845p9

name: NPR
text: More women are farming, but they're dealing with tools and machinery that can require a lot of upper body strength. Tractors can present serious challenges, including switching out heavy attachments and lifting fuel cans up to top-loading tanks. @KOSURadio https://t.co/fsO3yGthbp
